Design philosophy

A perfect nursing AI must obey six laws.

Law 1: Nurse is author, AI is drafter

The AI may propose, summarize, pre-fill, and highlight.
The nurse remains the legal signer and final authority.

Law 2: Ambient first, typing last

The best chart entry is the one captured from reality directly:
	•	monitor feeds
	•	med scans
	•	call light events
	•	voice snippets
	•	task completion
	•	room entry/exit signals
	•	patient interaction summaries

Manual typing is fallback, not primary mode.

Law 3: One event, many destinations

If a nurse documents something once, the system should propagate it everywhere appropriate:
	•	progress note
	•	flowsheet
	•	handoff summary
	•	care plan updates
	•	quality triggers
	•	billing-supporting metadata where lawful and appropriate

Law 4: Structured truth, human language on top

The system should store a structured internal representation first, then generate:
	•	formal chart text
	•	concise summaries
	•	shift handoff language
	•	patient-friendly explanations

Law 5: Nothing fabricated

If uncertain, the system says:
	•	observed
	•	inferred
	•	missing
	•	needs confirmation

It must distinguish them clearly.

Law 6: Friction only where risk is high

Low-risk repetition should vanish.
High-risk actions should require deliberate confirmation.

