Core user experiences

A. Ambient charting

Nurse says while walking out:
“Room 12, dressing changed, moderate serosanguinous drainage, tolerated well.”

AI returns:
	•	wound care note draft
	•	dressing change task complete
	•	wound flowsheet suggestions
	•	reassessment reminder if needed

B. Med pass co-pilot

During med administration, AI watches:
	•	what was scanned
	•	what was given
	•	what follow-up documentation is normally required
	•	whether pain reassessment or vitals follow-up is due

It then preps the downstream charting automatically.

C. Assessment accelerator

Instead of 90 clicks, nurse performs assessment conversationally:
“Lungs clear upper, diminished bases, no distress, bowel sounds active, mild edema ankles bilaterally.”

AI maps that to the structured assessment form and drafts narrative language.

D. Exception-first charting

For stable patients, AI carries forward unchanged findings and asks only:
“What changed?”

This is far more humane than rebuilding sameness from zero.

E. End-of-shift compression

Five minutes before handoff:
	•	unresolved tasks
	•	notable changes
	•	response to interventions
	•	key overnight watchouts
	•	recommended handoff draft

